 documentation of a downtrodden Rome, it is as a universal tale of human striving that De Sica’s film has proved influential.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>“Bicycle Thieves not only embodies both aesthetically and politically the most important features of the Italian neorealist movement but also, with De Sica’s use of non-professional actors, social engagement and firm roots in the fabric of society, paved the way for hybridity in film and therefore the so-called ‘cinema of the real’.” <strong>Nico Marzano</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>“This painfully beautiful chronicle of life in post-World War II Rome salvages views of rundown streets, poverty and injustice with such precision and simplicity that the emotional punch of the finale is unparalleled.” <strong>Kaya Genç</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>“The gold standard for all human films about inequality.” <strong>Andrei Liimets</strong></p>\r\n","quote":null,"credits":{"director":"Vittorio De Sica","producer":"","writer":"Oreste Biancoli, Suso Cecchi D'amico, Vittorio De Sica, Adolfo Franci, Gherardo Gherardi, Gerardo Guerrieri, Cesare Zavattini","featuring":"Lamberto Maggiorani, Enzo Staiola, Lianella Carell"},"year":"1948","nameAndYear":"Bicycle Thieves (1948)","links":{"player":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscription/film/watch-bicycle-thieves-1948-online","southbank":""},"player":{"url":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscription/film/watch-bicycle-thieves-1948-online","cta":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscribe/1283","pillar":"subscription","price":0,"duration":0},"performances":[],"tags":["BFI Player"],"productionCountries":"Italy","runningTime":96,"sightAndSound":{"results":[{"position":41,"tied":true,"category":"critics"},{"position":20,"tied":true,"category":"directors"}],"voters":null},"products":[]},{"uuid":"8803865c-9135-5c8f-b36f-6e50ffcb4873","image":{"base":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/","relative":"2022-11/the-400-blows-1959-jean-pierre-leaud-wire.jpeg","main":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles